Condyloid Joints
Condyloid joints consist of an ovalshaped end of one bone fitting into a similarly ovalshaped hollow of
another bone Figure 3830 This is also sometimes called an ellipsoidal joint This type of joint allows angular
movement along two axes as seen in the joints of the wrist and fingers which can move both side to side and
up and down
Figure 3830 The metacarpophalangeal joints in the finger are examples of condyloid joints credit modification of
work by Grays Anatomy
